  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The overwhelming majority of Queensland property sales are completed without a formal dispute between the seller and their agent. A competent agent, a clear agency agreement, and regular communication resolve most friction before it escalates into something serious. But agent conduct issues do occur: misrepresentation of a property's potential value to win a listing, failure to disclose a conflict of interest, misleading marketing claims, poor handling of offers, or simply ignoring a client's instructions. When something has genuinely gone wrong, sellers often do not know what steps are available to them or where to start.</p>

      <p>This article explains the complaint pathways available in Queensland, in order of escalation, and what you can realistically expect from each one.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Step one: raise it with the agency principal</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, a licensed real estate agent who operates under an agency is supervised by the agency's principal, who holds a real estate agent's licence and is legally responsible for the conduct of the salespeople under them. If your complaint is about the behaviour of a salesperson rather than the agency owner themselves, the first step is almost always to raise the issue in writing with the principal.</p>

      <p>Many complaints are resolved at this level. Agency principals have a commercial and regulatory interest in addressing conduct issues quickly. A written complaint to the principal creates a paper trail and puts the agency on notice that the issue is formal, not just a verbal grumble. In many cases, a clear written account of what occurred and what you expect to happen is enough to get the matter resolved without further escalation.</p>

      <p>If the issue is with the principal personally, or if the agency's response is unsatisfactory, the next steps are through Queensland's regulatory bodies.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Document everything before you escalate</h2>
      <p>Before you go further, assemble your evidence. Written records carry far more weight in any formal complaint process than verbal accounts. Gather all emails and text messages between you and the agent, signed copies of the agency agreement and any amendments, the listing and marketing materials the agent produced, and any written instructions you gave the agent and any responses to them.</p>

      <p>If there were conversations that are relevant, write down what was said, by whom, and when, as soon as possible. Your recollection will be more accurate now than in six months when a formal process is underway. Dates, times, and specific words matter in formal complaints. Generalisations do not carry the same weight.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Step two: the Office of Fair Trading</h2>
      <p>The Office of Fair Trading (OFT) is Queensland's regulatory body for licensed property agents. If your complaint involves conduct that may breach the Property Occupations Act 2014 (Qld), the OFT is the appropriate place to lodge a formal complaint. Relevant breaches include misrepresentation, failure to disclose a material conflict of interest, operating without a licence or outside the scope of a licence, and misconduct in handling trust monies.</p>

      <p>Complaints to the OFT can be made online through the Queensland Government website. You will be asked to describe the conduct, identify the agent by licence number if possible, and provide any supporting documentation. The OFT will assess whether the conduct falls within its jurisdiction and whether an investigation is warranted.</p>

      <p>What the OFT can do is significant in terms of protecting future consumers: it can investigate the agent, issue a formal warning, impose conditions on the agent's licence, and in serious cases suspend or cancel the licence entirely. What the OFT cannot do is award you financial compensation. If you have suffered a financial loss because of the agent's conduct, the OFT process will not recover that for you. For compensation, you need QCAT.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Step three: QCAT for financial compensation</h2>
      <p>The Queensland Civil and Administrative Tribunal (QCAT) hears civil disputes including claims against real estate agents where a seller has suffered a quantifiable financial loss because of the agent's conduct. If, for example, an agent's misrepresentation caused you to accept an offer significantly below market value, or an agent's failure to follow your instructions resulted in a demonstrable loss, QCAT is the forum for seeking damages.</p>

      <p>QCAT proceedings are more formal than an OFT complaint and typically involve a hearing where both parties present their case and evidence. You can represent yourself, though legal advice is strongly recommended before you file, particularly if the amount in dispute is significant. QCAT does not operate as a rubber stamp: you need to establish that the agent's conduct was in breach of their legal duties and that this breach caused the financial loss you are claiming. Evidence quality matters considerably.</p>

      <p>Time limits apply to QCAT claims. The general limitation period for civil claims in Queensland is three years from when the cause of action arose, but specific time limits may apply depending on the nature of the claim. Do not delay seeking advice. The longer you wait, the harder it becomes to gather evidence, locate witnesses, and mount a credible case.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What about the REIQ?</h2>
      <p>The Real Estate Institute of Queensland (REIQ) is a voluntary industry body, not a regulator. REIQ member agents are subject to the REIQ Code of Ethics, which covers professional conduct standards. If your agent is an REIQ member, you can lodge a complaint with the REIQ, and they will investigate whether the code has been breached.</p>

      <p>The practical limitation is that the REIQ has no statutory enforcement powers. It cannot compel an agent to pay compensation, and it cannot suspend or revoke a licence. Its disciplinary outcomes are limited to warnings, censure, and in the most serious cases expulsion from the REIQ. An expelled agent can still hold a Queensland licence and continue to operate. The REIQ complaint path is worth pursuing if your agent is a member and you want the conduct documented at an industry level, but it should not be your primary avenue if you have suffered financial harm.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Act promptly</h2>
      <p>The single most common mistake sellers make in complaint situations is waiting too long. Evidence becomes harder to gather. Witnesses' recollections fade. Time limits on formal processes approach. If you believe your agent has acted improperly and you want to preserve your options, start documenting and seeking advice while the transaction is still fresh. A conversation with a Queensland property solicitor early in the process will clarify which path is most appropriate for your situation and what evidence you need to support it.</p>

      <p>Most sellers who have a difficult experience with an agent never have cause to use these mechanisms, because most agents in Queensland operate professionally and competently. But the mechanisms exist precisely because things do go wrong, and knowing where to turn and how to proceed is the difference between having options and feeling stuck with no recourse.</p>

